# {{ project_name }} - Coding Standards

## Go Style Guide

This project follows standard Go conventions: [Effective Go](https://go.dev/doc/effective_go) and the community [Go Code Review Comments](https://go.dev/wiki/CodeReviewComments).

**Key Points:**
- Formatting is enforced by `gofmt` - never hand-format, run `make fmt`
- Indentation: tabs (gofmt's default, not configurable)
- Imports: grouped (standard library, then third-party) and sorted; `goimports` handles this automatically
- Package names: short, lowercase, no underscores or mixedCaps

## Naming Conventions

### Packages
```go
// Good
package cli
package config

// Bad
package CLI       // no initialisms in package names
package cli_utils  // no underscores
```

### Exported vs. Unexported
```go
// Exported: PascalCase, needs a doc comment
// Execute runs the CLI application.
func Execute() error { ... }

// Unexported: camelCase, doc comment optional but encouraged for non-trivial logic
func parseLogLevel(level string) slog.Level { ... }
```

### Variables and Constants
```go
// Good
var defaultTimeout = 30 * time.Second
const maxRetries = 3

// Acronyms stay uppercase
var apiURL string
var userID int
```

## Code Organization

### File Structure
```go
// Package doc comment (one file per package needs this)
package cli

import (
	// standard library first
	"fmt"
	"os"

	// then third-party, alphabetized
	"github.com/spf13/cobra"

	// then local packages
	"{{ module_path if module_path else project_name | snake_case }}/internal/version"
)

// Exported types and functions first, doc-commented
// ...

// Unexported helpers last
// ...
```

### Import Order
1. Standard library
2. Third-party modules
3. Local (this module's) packages

`goimports` (or `make fmt` if it's wired to run it) keeps this ordered automatically - don't hand-sort.

## Documentation Standards

### Doc Comments
```go
// Load reads configuration from path. If the file does not exist, the
// default configuration is returned instead of an error.
func Load(path string) (*Config, error) {
	// ...
}
```

Doc comments start with the identifier's name and are complete sentences. `go doc` and `pkg.go.dev` render these directly.

## Error Handling

### Always Check and Wrap Errors
```go
// Good
data, err := os.ReadFile(path)
if err != nil {
	return fmt.Errorf("reading config %s: %w", path, err)
}

// Bad
data, _ := os.ReadFile(path)  // silently swallows the error
```

### Sentinel and Typed Errors
```go
var ErrNotFound = errors.New("not found")

// Check with errors.Is / errors.As, not string comparison
if errors.Is(err, ErrNotFound) {
	// ...
}
```

### Don't Panic in Library Code
`internal/cli`, `internal/config`, and `internal/version` should return errors, not panic. Only `cmd/main.go` decides what happens on failure (it calls `os.Exit(1)`).

